@c    1 Paralipomenon Chapter 10


@c    Saul is slain for his sins:  he is buried by the men of Jabes.

@c    10:1. Now the Philistines fought against Israel, and the men of Israel
@c    fled from before the Philistines, and fell down wounded in mount
@c    Gelboe.

@c    10:2. And the Philistines drew near pursuing after Saul, and his sons,
@c    and they killed Jonathan, and Abinadab, and Melchisua the sons of Saul.

@c    10:3. And the battle grew hard against Saul and the archers reached
@c    him, and wounded him with arrows.

@c    10:4. And Saul said to his armourbearer:  Draw thy sword, and kill me:
@c    lest these uncircumcised come, and mock me.  But his armourbearer would
@c    not, for he was struck with fear:  so Saul took his sword, and fell upon
@c    it.

@c    10:5. And when his armourbearer saw it, to wit, that Saul was dead, he
@c    also fell upon his sword and died.

@c    10:6. So Saul died, and his three sons, and all his house fell
@c    together.

@c    10:7. And when the men of Israel, that dwelt in the plains, saw this,
@c    they fled:  and Saul and his sons being dead, they forsook their cities,
@c    and were scattered up and down:  and the Philistines came, and dwelt in
@c    them.

@c    10:8. And the next day the Philistines taking away the spoils of them
@c    that were slain, found Saul and his sons lying on mount Gelboe.

@c    10:9. And when they had stripped him, and out off his head, and taken
@c    away his armour, they sent it into their land, to be carried about, and
@c    shewn in the temples of the idols and to the people.

@c    10:10. And his armour they dedicated in the temple of their god, and
@c    his head they fastened up in the temple of Dagon.

@c    10:11. And when the men of Jabes Galaad had heard this, to wit, all
@c    that the Philistines had done to Saul,

@c    10:12. All the valiant men of them arose, and took the bodies of Saul
@c    and of his sons, and brought them to Jabes, and buried their bones
@c    under the oak that was in Jabes, and they fasted seven days.

@c    10:13. So Saul died for his iniquities, because he transgressed the
@c    commandment of the Lord, which he had commanded, and kept it not:  and
@c    moreover consulted also a witch,

@c    10:14. And trusted not in the Lord:  therefore he slew him, and
@c    transferred his kingdom to David the son of Isai.



@c    1 Paralipomenon Chapter 11


@c    David is made king.  He taketh the castle of Sion.  A catalogue of his
@c    valiant men.

@c    11:1. Then all Israel gathered themselves to David in Hebron, saying:
@c    We are thy bone, and thy flesh.

@c    11:2. Yesterday also, and the day before when Saul was king, thou wast
@c    he that leddest out and broughtest in Israel:  for the Lord thy God said
@c    to thee:  Thou shalt feed my people Israel, and thou shalt be ruler over
@c    them.

@c    11:3. So all the ancients of Israel came to the king to Hebron, and
@c    David made a covenant with them before the Lord:  and they anointed him
@c    king over Israel according to the word of the Lord which he spoke in
@c    the hand of Samuel.

@c    11:4. And David and all Israel went to Jerusalem, which is Jebus, where
@c    the Jebusites were the inhabitants of the land.

@c    11:5. And the inhabitants of Jebus said to David:  Thou shalt not come
@c    in here.  But David took the castle of Sion, which is the city of David.

@c    11:6. And he said:  Whosoever shall first strike the Jebusites, shall be
@c    the head and chief captain.  And Joab the son of Sarvia went up first,
@c    and was made the general.

@c    11:7. And David dwelt in the castle, and therefore it was called the
@c    city of David,

@c    11:8. And he built the city round about from Mello all round, and Joab
@c    built the rest of the city.

@c    11:9. And David went on growing and increasing, and the Lord of hosts
@c    was with him.

@c    11:10. These are the chief of the valiant man of David, who helped him
@c    to be made king over all Israel, according to the word of the Lord,
@c    which he spoke to Israel.

@c    11:11. And this is the number of the heroes of David:  Jesbaam the son
@c    of Hachamoni the chief among the thirty:  he lifted up his spear against
@c    three hundred wounded by him at one time.

@c    11:12. And after him was Eleazar his uncle's son the Ahohite, who was
@c    one of the three mighties.

@c    11:13. He was with David in Phesdomim, when the Philistines were
@c    gathered to that place to battle:  and the field of that country was
@c    full of barley, and the people fled from before the Philistines.

@c    11:14. But these men stood in the midst of the field, and defended it:
@c    and they slew the Philistines, and the Lord gave a great deliverance to
@c    his people.

@c    11:15. And three of the thirty captains went down to the rock, wherein
@c    David was, to the cave of Odollam, when the Philistines encamped in the
@c    valley of Raphaim.

@c    11:16. And David was in a hold, and the garrison of the Philistines in
@c    Bethlehem.

@c    11:17. And David longed, and said:  O that some man would give me water
@c    of the cistern of Bethlehem, which is in the gate.

@c    11:18. And these three broke through the midst of the camp of the
@c    Philistines, and drew water out of the cistern of Bethlehem, which was
@c    in the gate, and brought it to David to drink:  and he would not drink
@c    of it, but rather offered it to the Lord,

@c    11:19. Saying:  God forbid that I should do this in the sight of my God,
@c    and should drink the blood of these men:  for with the danger of their
@c    lives they have brought me the water.  And therefore he would not drink.
@c    These things did the three most valiant.

@c    11:20. And Abisai the brother of Joab, he was chief of three, and he
@c    lifted up his spear against three hundred whom he slew, and he was
@c    renowned among the three,

@c    11:21. And illustrious among the second three, and their captain:  but
@c    yet he attained not to the first three.

@c    11:22. Banaias the son of Joiada a most valiant man, of Cabseel, who
@c    had done many acts:  he slew the two ariels of Moab:  and he went down,
@c    and killed a lion in the midst of a pit in the time of snow.

@c    Two ariels. . .That is, two lions, or lion-like men; for Ariel in Hebrew
@c    signifies a lion.

@c    11:23. And he slew an Egyptian, whose stature was of five cubits, and
@c    who had a spear like a weaver's beam:  and he went down to him with a
@c    staff, and plucked away the spear, that he held in his hand, and slew
@c    him with his own spear.

@c    11:24. These things did Banaias the son of Joiada, who was renowned
@c    among the three valiant ones,

@c    11:25. And the first among the thirty, but yet to the three he attained
@c    not:  and David made him of his council.

@c    11:26. Moreover the most valiant men of the army, were Asahel brother
